1ï¸âƒ£ Creating Virtual DOM & Rendering into Actual DOM

React creates a Virtual DOM (lightweight copy of real DOM) and then renders it into the Actual DOM.

ğŸ”¹ React up to 17.x version
ReactDOM.render(
  <Component />,
  document.getElementById("root")
);


ğŸ“Œ ReactDOM.render()

Creates Virtual DOM

Renders it into Actual DOM

Used till React 17

ğŸ”¹ React 18.x & 19.x version (Modern Way)
const root = ReactDOM.createRoot(
  document.getElementById("root")
);

root.render(<Component />);


ğŸ“Œ Why new method?

Supports Concurrent Rendering

Better performance

Recommended for modern React

2ï¸âƒ£ Installing Required Libraries for React Project

Run the following commands in terminal:

npm install react@18 --save
npm install react-dom@18 --save
npm install @babel/standalone --save


OR (single line):

npm install react@18 --save react-dom@18 --save @babel/standalone --save

ğŸ“Œ What happens after installation?

All libraries are downloaded into:

node_modules


These libraries must be linked to HTML file (for non-build projects).

3ï¸âƒ£ Linking React Libraries in HTML
<script src="../node_modules/react/umd/react.development.js"></script>
<script src="../node_modules/react-dom/umd/react-dom.development.js"></script>
<script src="../node_modules/@babel/standalone/babel.js"></script>

4ï¸âƒ£ Writing Custom React Script

Your React code is written inside <script> tag.

Script Types Supported:

text/babel

text/jsx

<script type="text/babel">
  // React code here
</script>

5ï¸âƒ£ React Components
ğŸ”¹ What is a Component?

A React Component is a reusable UI block.

A component consists of:

Design â†’ HTML

Style â†’ CSS

Logic â†’ JSX / TSX

ğŸ“Œ Technically, a component is a JavaScript:

Function âœ… (recommended)

Class âŒ (supported but not recommended)

ğŸ”¹ Recommended Component Type (React 18 / 19)

âœ” Function Component

Class components are:

Old

Verbose

Not recommended in modern React

6ï¸âƒ£ Component Rules (Very Important)

A component must be a JavaScript function

Can be created using:

Function declaration

Function expression

Component name must start with Uppercase letter

Component cannot be void

Component must return JSX

7ï¸âƒ£ Component Syntax
âœ… Function Declaration
function Login() {
  return <h1>Login Page</h1>;
}

âœ… Function Expression
const Login = function () {
  return <h1>Login Page</h1>;
};

8ï¸âƒ£ Component Must Return JSX

âŒ Invalid (returns nothing)

function Login() {
}


âœ” Valid

function Login() {
  return <h1>Hello</h1>;
}

9ï¸âƒ£ JSX Return Rules
âŒ Returning multiple elements directly (INVALID)
return (
  <h1>Hello</h1>
  <p>Welcome</p>
);

âœ… Correct Way (Single Parent Element)
return (
  <div>
    <h1>Hello</h1>
    <p>Welcome</p>
  </div>
);


OR using semantic tags:

return (
  <header>
    <h1>Hello</h1>
    <p>Welcome</p>
  </header>
);

ğŸ”Ÿ JSX Self-Closing & Token Rules

Every JSX element must have a closing tag.

âŒ Invalid
<img>
<input>

âœ… Valid
<img />
<input />


OR

<img></img>
<input></input>

1ï¸âƒ£1ï¸âƒ£ JSX Uses Properties, Not Attributes
âŒ Invalid (HTML style)
<img class="logo">

âœ… Valid (JSX style)
<img className="logo" />


ğŸ“Œ JSX uses:

className instead of class

htmlFor instead of for

1ï¸âƒ£2ï¸âƒ£ Important Notes (Interview Ready)

JSX looks like HTML but is JavaScript

React re-renders UI using Virtual DOM

Function components are default choice

JSX must return one root element

Every JSX tag must be closed

âœ… Final Summary

ğŸ‘‰ Modern React (18/19):

Uses createRoot

Uses function components

Uses JSX

Uses Virtual DOM for performance
